{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_018VfmPNuXoo5q2TyVVGaJxq","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package com.coffeeshop.orders.web;\n     2→\n     3→import jakarta.validation.ConstraintViolation;\n     4→import jakarta.validation.ConstraintViolationException;\n     5→import jakarta.ws.rs.core.MediaType;\n     6→import jakarta.ws.rs.core.Response;\n     7→import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.ExceptionMapper;\n     8→import jakarta.ws.rs.ext.Provider;\n     9→\n    10→import java.util.List;\n    11→import java.util.Map;\n    12→\n    13→@Provider\n    14→public class ConstraintViolationExceptionMapper implements ExceptionMapper<ConstraintViolationException> {\n    15→\n    16→  @Override\n    17→  public Response toResponse(ConstraintViolationException ex) {\n    18→    List<Map<String, String>> errors = ex.getConstraintViolations().stream()\n    19→        .map(this::toEntry)\n    20→        .toList();\n    21→    return Response.status(Response.Status.BAD_REQUEST)\n    22→        .type(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON_TYPE)\n    23→        .entity(Map.of(\"errors\", errors))\n    24→        .build();\n    25→  }\n    26→\n    27→  private Map<String, String> toEntry(ConstraintViolation<?> v) {\n    28→    String field = v.getPropertyPath() == null ? \"\" : v.getPropertyPath().toString();\n    29→    return Map.of(\"field\", field, \"message\", v.getMessage());\n    30→  }\n    31→}\n    32→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8c0436c-69f4-4378-aa8f-dd3eb0ddb087","uuid":"dcae5a81-4523-403b-89ee-894683a85b01"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01RNG1KWXDvunK5bJ4sN4RAF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→package com.coffeeshop.orders.health;\n     2→\n     3→import org.eclipse.microprofile.health.HealthCheck;\n     4→import org.eclipse.microprofile.health.HealthCheckResponse;\n     5→import org.eclipse.microprofile.health.Readiness;\n     6→import jakarta.enterprise.context.ApplicationScoped;\n     7→\n     8→@Readiness\n     9→@ApplicationScoped\n    10→public class BasicHealth implements HealthCheck {\n    11→    @Override\n    12→    public HealthCheckResponse call() {\n    13→        return HealthCheckResponse.up(\"orders-service\");\n    14→    }\n    15→}\n    16→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8c0436c-69f4-4378-aa8f-dd3eb0ddb087","uuid":"65cdb2eb-befe-44ca-88c4-d2c34c105e4c"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01J2gCSTXAGLM9iDkgZJC7di","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good. Everything looks correct. Now let me also check there's a potential issue with Quarkus validation: when Quarkus RESTEasy Reactive (quarkus-rest-jackson) processes a `@Valid` parameter, it may throw a `ResteasyReactiveViolationException` rather than a plain `ConstraintViolationException`. However, `ResteasyReactiveViolationException` extends `ConstraintViolationException`, so the mapper should still catch it. But Quarkus also has its own built-in violation mapper that might take precedence. Let me verify this won't be a problem.\n\nActually, looking at the pom, we're using `quarkus-rest-jackson` which is RESTEasy Reactive. Quarkus has a built-in `ConstraintViolationExceptionMapper` for RESTEasy Reactive that returns 400 with violation details. So our custom one should work or Quarkus's built-in will handle it. Either way, validation errors should return 400.\n\nNow let me also check a potential issue: the `@Valid` annotation is on `OrderService.place()`, not on `OrdersResource.place()`. For Quarkus RESTEasy to validate at the resource level, we need `@Valid` on the resource method parameter. Let me check if the current setup will work...\n\nLooking at the code:\n- `OrdersResource.place(OrderRequest req)` - no `@Valid` on the parameter\n- `OrderService.place(@Valid OrderRequest req)` - has `@Valid` \n\nFor Quarkus, validation at the CDI bean level (OrderService) should still work with `quarkus-hibernate-validator`. The `@Valid` on the service method parameter will trigger validation when the service method is called. So validation should work.\n\nNow let me check one more thing - the parent pom to make sure everything will build:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1362,"cache_read_input_tokens":41100,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1362,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":541},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8c0436c-69f4-4378-aa8f-dd3eb0ddb087","uuid":"d61e13a8-3e20-4533-9a28-038a16a3a289"}
