{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_bdrk_01BitkUJs6qKLA2QC6FxdKCX","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→<project xmlns=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0\"\n     2→         xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\"\n     3→         xsi:schemaLocation=\"http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0\n     4→                             https://maven.apache.org/xsd/maven-4.0.0.xsd\">\n     5→  <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion>\n     6→  <artifactId>common</artifactId>\n     7→  <packaging>jar</packaging>\n     8→  <parent>\n     9→    <groupId>com.coffeeshop</groupId>\n    10→    <artifactId>coffeeshop-quarkus</artifactId>\n    11→    <version>0.2.0-SNAPSHOT</version>\n    12→    <relativePath>../pom.xml</relativePath>\n    13→  </parent>\n    14→  <dependencies>\n    15→    <dependency>\n    16→      <groupId>jakarta.validation</groupId>\n    17→      <artifactId>jakarta.validation-api</artifactId>\n    18→    </dependency>\n    19→    <dependency>\n    20→      <groupId>com.fasterxml.jackson.core</groupId>\n    21→      <artifactId>jackson-databind</artifactId>\n    22→    </dependency>\n    23→  </dependencies>\n    24→</project>\n    25→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8c0436c-69f4-4378-aa8f-dd3eb0ddb087","uuid":"1781c74e-2904-489e-bd5d-d9adfe0e401b"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01M3bYi8a3ntevJR7a5yzLNM","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The common module has `jakarta.validation-api` which provides the constraint annotations. The orders-service has `quarkus-hibernate-validator` which provides the actual validator implementations. In a regular Quarkus app, `@NotBlank` on a `String` field works fine.\n\nThe issue might be with how the uber-jar packages the validator. Let me think about this differently...\n\nActually, the error says `validating type 'java.lang.String'` for `@NotBlank`. The `@NotBlank` constraint is defined with `@Target({ METHOD, FIELD, ANNOTATION_TYPE, CONSTRUCTOR, PARAMETER, TYPE_USE })` and applies to `CharSequence`. In Quarkus with `hibernate-validator`, there should be a built-in `NotBlankValidator` for `CharSequence`.\n\nThe problem might be that Quarkus's build-time optimization removes the `NotBlankValidator` because during augmentation it doesn't detect that `@NotBlank` is used on the `OrderRequest` class (since `OrderRequest` is in the `common` module which is not a Quarkus extension). \n\nLet me try a workaround - use `@NotNull` and `@Size(min=1)` instead of `@NotBlank`:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":977,"cache_read_input_tokens":86213,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":977,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":412},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c8c0436c-69f4-4378-aa8f-dd3eb0ddb087","uuid":"6fbd6a18-0de9-402e-a1e9-b6cdc9cf3ed1"}
